Task 1: Use Vagrant to Simulate Physical Security Gaps
Subtask 1.1: Initialize Vagrant Environment
First, we'll create a Vagrant environment that simulates a network with physical security vulnerabilities.

Open a terminal and create a new directory for the lab:
mkdir ~/physical-security-lab
cd ~/physical-security-lab
Initialize a new Vagrant environment:
vagrant init ubuntu/focal64
Create a custom Vagrantfile to simulate multiple network interfaces (representing physical network access points):
cat > Vagrantfile << 'EOF'
Vagrant.configure("2") do |config|
  config.vm.box = "ubuntu/focal64"
  config.vm.hostname = "security-test-vm"
  
  # Configure multiple network interfaces to simulate physical access points
  config.vm.network "private_network", ip: "192.168.56.10", name: "vboxnet0"
  config.vm.network "private_network", ip: "10.0.0.10", name: "vboxnet1"
  
  # Port forwarding to simulate exposed services
  config.vm.network "forwarded_port", guest: 22, host: 2222
  config.vm.network "forwarded_port", guest: 80, host: 8080
  config.vm.network "forwarded_port", guest: 21, host: 2121
  
  config.vm.provider "virtualbox" do |vb|
    vb.memory = "1024"
    vb.cpus = 2
    vb.name = "PhysicalSecurityGap"
  end
  
  # Provision the VM with vulnerable services
  config.vm.provision "shell", inline: <<-SHELL
    apt-get update
    apt-get install -y apache2 vsftpd telnetd python3-pip tcpdump
    
    # Configure Apache with default page
    systemctl enable apache2
    systemctl start apache2
    
    # Configure FTP with anonymous access (security gap)
    echo "anonymous_enable=YES" >> /etc/vsftpd.conf
    echo "write_enable=YES" >> /etc/vsftpd.conf
    systemctl enable vsftpd
    systemctl start vsftpd
    
    # Enable telnet (insecure protocol)
    systemctl enable inetd
    systemctl start inetd
    
    # Install Python packages for monitoring
    pip3 install scapy psutil
    
    echo "Vulnerable services configured successfully"
  SHELL
end
EOF
Start the Vagrant virtual machine:
vagrant up
